Question:-
The n-queens puzzle is the problem of placing n queens on an n x n chessboard such that no two queens attack each other.

Given an integer n, return the number of distinct solutions to the n-queens puzzle.

Solution:-
This Problem is Almost Similar to N-Queens what extra we have to done over here is, Instead of printing the position we have to count the no. of ways in which Queens can be arranged on N-By-N chess

Code:-

class Solution {
    public int totalNQueens(int n) {
        char board[][] = new char[n][n];
        for(char i[] : board)
            Arrays.fill(i, '.');
        return dfs(0, board);
    }
    public int dfs(int col, char board[][]){
        if(col == board.length) return 1;
        int count = 0;
        for(int row = 0; row < board.length; row++){
            if(isSafe(board, row, col)){
                board[row][col] = 'Q';
                count += dfs(col + 1, board);
                board[row][col] = '.';
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
    public boolean isSafe(char board[][], int row, int col){
        int dupRow = row;
        int dupCol = col;
        
        while(row >= 0 && col >= 0){
            if(board[row][col] == 'Q') return false;
            row--;
            col--;
        }
        
        row = dupRow;
        col = dupCol;
        while(col >= 0){
            if(board[row][col] == 'Q') return false;
            col--;
        }
        
        row = dupRow;
        col = dupCol;
        while(col >= 0 && row < board.length){
            if(board[row][col] == 'Q') return false;
            row++;
            col--;
        }
        return true;
    }
}

TC : O(N! * N)
SC : O(N^2)
